# API Logging Rules

Centralized logging via `ApiRequestLoggingFilter` and `GlobalExceptionHandler`. Do not duplicate request logging in controllers.

## Log levels

| Event | Level | Location |
|-------|-------|----------|
| HTTP request summary (method, path, status, duration) | INFO | `ApiRequestLoggingFilter` |
| Query string, user id, JSON/text req/res bodies (truncated) | DEBUG | `ApiRequestLoggingFilter` |
| 4xx (`ResponseStatusException`, validation, 403, 401) | WARN | `GlobalExceptionHandler` |
| Unhandled 5xx | ERROR + stack | `GlobalExceptionHandler` |

## Configuration

`application.yml`:

- `logging.level.com.highsteak.api` — `${APP_LOG_LEVEL:INFO}`
- `logging.level.com.highsteak.api.config.ApiRequestLoggingFilter` — `${APP_HTTP_LOG_LEVEL:INFO}`
- `app.logging.http-access-enabled` — `${HTTP_ACCESS_LOG_ENABLED:true}`
- `app.logging.skip-paths` — `/health`, `/swagger-ui`, `/v3/api-docs`, `/uploads`

Spring Boot override: `LOGGING_LEVEL_COM_HIGHSTEAK_API=DEBUG`

## Never log (even at DEBUG)

- JWT tokens or `Authorization` headers
- Request/response bodies on `/auth/*` (tokens and passwords)
- Multipart file bytes (logged as `[multipart omitted]`)

## Service-level logs

Add `@Slf4j` DEBUG logs in services only for non-obvious business events (e.g. failed external call). Do not log every CRUD operation.

## Examples

```java
// BAD — per-controller request logging
@GetMapping
public List<PostResponse> getFeed(HttpServletRequest request) {
    log.info("GET /posts from {}", request.getRemoteAddr());
    return steakPostService.getFeed();
}

// GOOD — filter handles it; controller stays thin
@GetMapping
public List<PostResponse> getFeed() {
    return steakPostService.getFeed();
}
```

```java
// BAD
System.out.println("User logged in: " + password);

// GOOD
log.debug("Registered user {}", username);
```

